Very eloquently put, Sparrowhawk.<br><br>
My Grandfather taught me never to judge a man by anything until you know what he is made of when the chips are down. I'm afraid Spatz doesn't have any chips.<br><br>
As I observed some time ago, which this latest induced psychodrama reinforces, is that Spatz emotionally feeds off of the contentious situations he deliberately creates. The last thing many Nam Vets need is a destructive parasitism of their emotional rocky road. It is one thing to discuss, debate, agree, and disagree, and to talk about the good and the bad times. It is quite another thing to periodically put down someone else with nothing more than hollow adolescent schoolyard bully tactics or comments, or go about masquerading as Vald the Impailer.<br><br>
The Vietnam War, and all of its horror, sadness, and sometimes macabre joy, was very real. Those who served were not cowards. Those who served looked death straight in the eye, and experienced and learned things that were truly outside the realm of common experience. Life in the extreme touched all of us to one degree or another, some more, some less, but we were all included in the end. Most all protestors with whom I have interacted respect that at least as a minimum, and want to learn and discuss in a civil, constructive manner, and for which I reciprocate. We were there, and nothing is ever going to change that, ever.<br><br>
Those who fail to respect that barest minimum of fact are truly not worth the time of day.<br><br>
Detonate Zulu     
